{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488325"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:37:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:37:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"413"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/413"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.24,0.45,0.04,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"413"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98543"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/413"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"413"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80948"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3526"},{"type":"tags","id":"3527"},{"type":"tags","id":"3874"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"190"},{"type":"contributions","id":"216"},{"type":"contributions","id":"259"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15544"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16278"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33779"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39628"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42079"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45050"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98543"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a two-month history of fatigue and lethargy. She is otherwise in good health but finds that her current symptoms have curtailed her real estate business activities. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Physical examination is otherwise unremarkable. Screening tests are notable for elevated serum calcium of 2.72 mmol/L and 2.76 mmol/L (2.15-2.55) on two separate occasions. Further tests reveal an abnormally high parathyroid hormone level.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["DEXA scan","CT head and neck","Sestamibi scan","PET scan","MRI neck"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn highly resourced health care settings, where patients are routinely screened, patients with primary hyperparathyroidism typically present asymptomatically with moderate hypercalcaemia and non-suppressed to high PTH levels. Up to 85% of cases are a result of a single parathyroid adenoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIndications for parathyroidectomy, the only curative treatment, remains an area of controversy. Generally symptomatic patients, or those with end-organ sequelae, are usually offered surgical intervention. Some investigations might be done at this stage to help determine the need for surgical intervention. As parathyroid imaging is not required to establish a diagnosis of primary hyperparathyroidism, the most appropriate next investigation in these circumstances would be a \u003Cstrong\u003EDEXA scan\u003C/strong\u003E to assess bone mineral density. Evidence of complications such as osteopaenia or osteoporosis (on DEXA scan) would aid in determining the need for and support advising parathyroidectomy. A thoracolumbar spinal x-ray should also be considered to exclude vertebral compression fractures, with a height loss of \u226520% consistent with minimal trauma fracture. Renal tract imaging (e.g., ultrasound, X-ray kidney/ureter/bladder, non-contrast CT kidney/ureter/bladder) could also be considered to exclude nephrolithiasis, another complication. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT head and neck\u003C/strong\u003E is not the initial investigation of choice in this scenario. While it can be useful for localizing parathyroid adenomas preoperatively, it is not necessary at this stage when the focus is on assessing end-organ effects of hyperparathyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESestamibi scan\u003C/strong\u003E is a nuclear medicine imaging technique used to localize parathyroid adenomas. It is typically performed after the decision for surgery has been made and is not the most appropriate next step in this patient\u0027s management. Given the vague symptoms and mild hypercalcaemia, surgery is not indicated upfront without further assessment of end-organ complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPET scan\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely used in the initial workup of primary hyperparathyroidism. It may occasionally be used in cases where other imaging modalities have failed to localize a parathyroid adenoma, but this is not the current clinical question.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI neck\u003C/strong\u003E, like CT, can be useful for localizing parathyroid adenomas. However, it is not the most appropriate next investigation when the priority is to assess for end-organ effects of hyperparathyroidism to guide management decisions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The presence of osteopenia in a patient with primary hyperparathyroidism will help in decision-making with regards to parathyroidectomy.","DEXA scan is the most appropriate initial investigation for assessing end-organ effects in primary hyperparathyroidism."],"references":["Blackburn M. Primary hyperparathyroidism and familial hyperparathyroid syndromes. Australian Family Physician. 2007;36(12). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18075629/","Insogna K. Primary Hyperparathyroidism. New England Journal of Medicine. 2018;379(11):1050-1059. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30207907/","Walker M, Silverberg S. Primary hyperparathyroidism. Nature Reviews Endocrinology. 2017;14(2):115-125. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28885621/","Milat F, Ramchand SK, Herath M, Gundara J, Harper S, Farrell S, et al. Primary hyperparathyroidism in adults\u2014(Part I) assessment and medical management: Position statement of the endocrine society of Australia, the Australian \u0026 New Zealand endocrine surgeons, and the Australian \u0026 New Zealand bone and mineral society. Clinical Endocrinology. 2021 Dec 21"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80948"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"413"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80948"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-14T17:08:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-14T17:10:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"413"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98543"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","sy